['Our results indicate that across countries, there is a correlation between income inequality and intergenerational mobility (Corak 2013; Corak et al. 2014; Krueger 2012; OECD 2011, 2015).', 'Differences between countries in the Great Gatsby curve could be a consequence in the degree of upward mobility for children of low-income parents (Corak 2013;
Corak et al. 2014).', 'Higher inequality is associated with lower economic mobility across generations (Corak 2013; Corak et al. 2014), likely as a result of economic improvement being more unequally allocated among children (Brunori, Ferreira, and Peragine 2013).', 'Our analysis suggests that there is a strong crosscountry association between income inequality and intergenerational mobility, as reported by previous studies (Corak 2013; Corak et al. 2014; Krueger 2012; OECD 2011, 2015).', 'This pattern confirms the results of previous studies, in which high inequality levels are negatively associated with intergenerational mobility (Corak 2013; Corak et al. 2014;
Krueger 2012; OECD 2011, 2015).', '…Gatsby curve
is a scatterplot used to illustrate the inverse relationship between income inequality and intergenerational mobility: Societies with higher levels of inequality tend to have lower levels of intergenerational mobility (Corak 2013; Corak, Lindquist, and Mazumder 2014; Krueger 2012).', 'Previous analyses have shown that income inequality is negatively correlated with intergenerational mobility in comparisons between countries at a given point in time (Corak 2013; Corak et al. 2014; Krueger 2012; OECD 2011, 2015).']
